title: New Hospital Authority Chairman appointed (with photo)
content_text:
p>
			The Government announced today (October 8) that, in accordance with 
			the Hospital Authority Ordinance, the Chief Executive has appointed 
			Professor John Leong Chi-yan as the Chairman of the Hospital 
			Authority (HA). His term of appointment will be two years with 
			effect from December 1, 2013. Professor Leong is an internationally renowned clinician-scientist 
			specialising in spinal and paediatric orthopaedics. He has served as

specialising in spinal and paediatric orthopaedics. He has served as 
			the President of the Open University of Hong Kong since 2003. He is 
			also an Emeritus Professor and an Honorary Professor of both the 
			Department of Orthopaedics and Traumatology and the Department of 
			Biochemistry of the University of Hong Kong. He was Chair Professor 
			and Head of the Department of Orthopaedic Surgery of the University 
			of Hong Kong, and Chief of Service of the Department of Orthopaedics

of Hong Kong, and Chief of Service of the Department of Orthopaedics 
			and Traumatology at Queen Mary Hospital from 1981 to 2003. He was 
			Dean of the Faculty of Medicine of the University of Hong Kong from 
			1985 to 1990. Professor Leong has rich exposure in community service. Currently, 
			he is the Chairman of the Citizens Advisory Committee on Community 
			Relations of the Independent Commission Against Corruption, the 
			Public Libraries Advisory Committee and the Consultation Panel under

Public Libraries Advisory Committee and the Consultation Panel under 
			the West Kowloon Cultural District Authority. He was also the 
			Chairman of the Hospital Governing Committee (HGC) of Castle Peak 
			Hospital from 1999 to 2013 and is now an HGC member of Ruttonjee 
			Hospital. The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr Ko Wing-man, welcomed the 
			appointment of Professor Leong as the new Chairman. He said 
			Professor Leong's vast experience in the health-care sector and

Professor Leong's vast experience in the health-care sector and 
			public service as well as thorough understanding of the HA's 
			operation made him eminently suitable for such an important post. "I have every confidence in Professor Leong that under his 
			leadership, the HA would be able to rise to the many challenges that 
			lie ahead and continue to provide the public with quality medical 
			services. In particular, his solid experience in managing public 
			organisations and sound knowledge on the health-care system of Hong

organisations and sound knowledge on the health-care system of Hong 
			Kong would be invaluable assets to the HA review under way," Dr Ko 
			said. He also thanked and commended the outgoing Chairman, Mr Anthony Wu 
			Ting-yuk, for his strong leadership and unwavering commitment that 
			he has demonstrated over the past nine years as Chairman of the HA. "I am sure that Mr Wu will continue to take a close interest in the 
			work of the Authority and support the Government in enhancing our

work of the Authority and support the Government in enhancing our health-care system and public hospital services in other capacities", Dr Ko said. Ends/Tuesday, October 8, 2013
Issued at HKT 14:01
